The women's basketball team failed to reach the WOC 17 medal, finishing fourth
The Americans also won the third WOC 17, defeating Spain just 77-75 in the final despite 40 points from Spain's Angela Salvadores.
"We wanted to win very much and not be potatoes, but maybe we wanted it too much. We caught the start, but we couldn't keep it because they overpowered us under the basket," lamented captain Karolína Malečková. "It was an incredible experience to play in front of such an audience," she praised the fans in Klatovy and Plzeň.
The Czechs started very well, taking an 8-0 lead thanks to two threes and dominating the field for the entire first quarter. At that moment it seemed that they would repay their opponents' 85-88 group defeat after extra time. But the referees whistled them 15 fouls at half-time and with questionable decisions helped Hungary return to the game with a 12-2 lead.
"I'm convinced that it was enough to make two more three baskets, run away to 20 points and we wouldn't let it go. But instead came our mistakes. I am not interested in the referees, but in what we did wrong and there were mistakes that helped the opponent to catch on," said coach Richard Fousek.
"It was not the first time we had a lapse in concentration. But the girls are fighters, they didn't let anything out and fought to the end. But the opponent was very good," he added.
The Czechs were kept in the game in particular by Petra Holešínská's accurate shooting from distance and the pivot Tereza Šípová. However, the best Czech scorer had a problem with fouls and a large part of the third quarter was missing on the pitch. The Hungarians took advantage and gained a slight lead, which they already held, although the Czechs fought until the last seconds.
"For us the first five games were very difficult, we turned the games in a tight rotation and it cost us a lot of strength. Even against Spain it was obvious that the girls were tired and there was no place to take. Because of the physicality we were not consistent in our defence. We didn't play a quick counter-attack, we lacked a rebound. And the Hungarians are of such quality that if you don't combine everything together you can hardly win," added Fousek.
He believes that his charge has a promising future. "In two years, the girls managed to win the Youth Olympics, to be second in the European 16-year-old championship and now they are fourth in the world. By our standards, they are a quality team with good character and it is necessary to work with them and develop their talent. Now it is up to the federation to assign a coach to them in the higher categories," added Fousek.
Thomas Cook: Czechs kicked out of hotel in Mallorca. Guarantees weren't enough
The Austrian, German and Polish divisions of the group also filed for insolvency in the week. The future of the Czech branch is currently being discussed, and a decision should be made by the end of September.
According to the vice-chairman of the Association of Travel Agencies of the Czech Republic, Jan Papež, there are three possible solutions in play - a liquidation will be announced, or the company will be sold, or a team from the Czech branch will set up a new travel agency. "Which one it will be, but it is impossible to predict, will be up to the German owner," he told ČTK today.
In addition to two early terminated trips, CK is also dealing with cases where clients had to pay for their stay out of their own pockets, although the company is trying to provide guarantees to hoteliers. CK has promised to reimburse its clients, according to Popež, the company has sufficient security to do so.
Problems in hotels arose mainly in Mallorca, where the company also asked the Czech consulate for help. In this context, the Pope described to the Czech News Agency one of the cases where the hotel there threw out all of the office's tourists. "The hotelier was unable to determine who belonged to the German company and who belonged to the Czech company. Therefore, it threw out all of the hotel despite the fact that the domestic Neckermann provided guarantees," he said. According to Šrámek, the situation was eventually resolved.
The Czech branch of the bankrupt British group Thomas Cook increased its sales to CZK 995 million last year, almost 21 percent more year-on-year, according to the company's annual report. It covers the financial period from October 2017 to the end of September 2018. The company's net profit, on the other hand, decreased by about seven million to CZK 15.3 million. However, the company has been left with an unpaid loss of almost CZK 103 million from previous years. The branch includes two basic divisions - besides CK Neckermann, it is also the company Global Travel Lufthansa City Center.
