Brno developers say they did not think of the brand famous for mobile phones in the past when creating the warehouse program. CCV's designation of Lokia is based on the Latin name for one type of dragonfly, whose rapid movement is supposed to be analogous to the movement of warehouse storekeepers around the warehouse.
"In the Czech market, the possibility of confusion is unlikely. We sell modern cloud software that companies equip their warehouse operations with, and we are not really heading into the field of mobile phone production. And we do not want to be compared to a brand that may be missing the train in its field," responded CCV manager Tomáš Kormaňák in E15.
CCV applied for brand protection in August before launching the program at the Industrial Property Office. "It applied for protection for products and services belonging to Classes 9, 35 and 42, as the software belongs to Class 9, the related warehouse business management services belong to Class 35, and the development of computer software belongs to Class 42 according to the international classification," said Ondrášek.
Nokia's objection is based on the fact that the earlier Nokia trademark is valid in all classes of goods and services and thus covers the widest possible range of goods and services and therefore of course overlaps also in Classes 9, 35 and 42. "CCV does not dispute the objection's assertion as far as the conformity of these classes of products and services is concerned. Realistically, however, these are completely different brands aimed at different target groups," said Ondrášek.
