Epilepsy complicated his love of sports, thanks to surgery he has a new hope
The first time Honza's parents noticed that something was wrong with him was in a year and a half. He would stare into space for a few minutes, freeze and not react to anyone. The pediatrician therefore sent him to the pediatric neurology clinic, where doctors, after a series of examinations, diagnosed him with epilepsy and immediately put him on medication, which however did not work immediately.
It took almost a year for doctors to find the ideal combination of medications, thanks to which he completely stopped having seizures. At the age of five, doctors stopped his medication, and since the seizures did not return, his parents thought that Honza was healthy and began to guide him more into sports. He rode his bike, skied, played tennis and floorball, spent his free time playing games with his sister and friends. At the age of eleven, however, he had another seizure and everything started anew.
Doctors tried different combinations of medications again, but this time nothing worked, the seizures in the form of absences were constantly repeated. Since during the seizure Honza always lost his senses, his parents were terrified that he would get it during sports and get injured. Gradually Honza stopped riding his bike and swapped downhill skis for cross-country skis and snowboard. Although from time to time the sport caused him to have a seizure, he never gave it up completely. He even fulfilled his dream and ran the Spartan Race, but together with a friend who kept an eye on him all the time to help in case of emergency.
When Honza was 15 years old, his parents decided to try to change doctors and turned to specialists at the Motol University Hospital Hospital. After a series of examinations, doctors there concluded that Honza was a candidate for surgery to remove a lesion from his brain - the source of his epileptic seizures. "I had to have 2 surgeries in a row, first the doctors inserted probes into my brain to scan his activity, then they could remove the lesion. It was a hell for several weeks. I just had to lie there and hardly move, with wires sticking out of my head that were connected to a computer," recalls Honza.
The operation was successful and the doctors removed a relatively large bearing. "The first days after the operation were very psychologically challenging, Honza was apathetic, confused, sad and hardly spoke. It was a scary change compared to how he is normally alive and communicative, but fortunately after a few days everything returned to normal," describes his mother and adds: "A month and a half after the operation he had 1 seizure, but according to the doctors it happens. Since then he has been seizure-free for 3 months."
This school year Honza will graduate, besides sports he enjoys languages and started working with E Company, with which he goes to meetings about epilepsy in schools. Honza is not fully engaged in sports activities yet, he starts to return to sports slowly. "I am learning how to play sports properly, how to breathe well so that I don't expose my body to sudden stress, which is quite a challenge with my competitive nature," explains Honza.
This year he will therefore not actively participate in the traditional EPPI boating triathlon, where epilepsy sufferers and healthy athletes meet and which takes place this weekend on 28 September 2019 at Veselská pískovně. But next year he will.
