Microplastics have reached the human gut, study confirms for the first time
Scientists have confirmed their suspicions over several years. A team led by University of Vienna professor Philipp Schwabl has published a study which, for the first time, proves the presence of microplastics in human stool. While the study is small, with eight participants from Europe, Japan and Russia, tiny particles of plastics measuring between 50 and 500 micrometres were found in samples of all the subjects studied. None of the eight subjects were vegetarians, six of them did not avoid sea fish, all drank water from plastic bottles and food packed in plastic.
And it would actually be a bit of a miracle if nothing was found. We already know that microplastics - which are either produced directly, for example, for the needs of the cosmetic industry, or are produced by breaking up larger pieces - are present in marine animals, insects, tap water and soft drinks; in short, everywhere on the planet. So their entry into the human digestive system has only been officially confirmed. There were roughly 20 microplastic particles per ten grams of stool, and scientists estimate that more than half of the world's population will have them in them.
Of course, both the layman and the scientific mind suspect that this is not a good thing. But humanity still does not know how bad it is - and what effect microplastics have on "host" organisms. Small particles can reach the bloodstream or the lymphatic system and end up in the liver, for example. "This is the first study of its kind, and it has confirmed what we have long thought. Now that we have the first evidence of microplastics in the human body, we must continue to investigate exactly what this means for human health," Schwabl says.
So far, it is known that microplastics in the gut can negatively affect the immune responses of the digestive system, making it easier for toxic chemicals and other pathogens to be absorbed into the body. And so far, there is no known solution other than to reduce the use of plastics, especially polypropylene. But that will be difficult - the first task facing governments and authorities will at least be to stop its steep rise. As for plastic bottles alone, experts estimate that in three years, mankind will consume one-fifth more than it does today. The current rate is a staggering one million bottles bought per minute. Every year, roughly eight million tons of plastic end up in the seas and oceans. Waste threatens marine ecosystems and poisons the digestive systems of marine animals.
Some countries have already taken restrictions and other measures; Kenya, for example - under threat of draconian penalties - has banned plastic bags. The European Commission is considering small bans (well-known straws), and the country's environment ministry is moving in the same direction. Critics, however, argue that such measures, while nice, are totally inadequate.
The repair of the Krkonoše museum will be a year late
The Krkonoše National Park Administration (KRNAP) has moved the deadline for submitting bids to the second tender for the repair of the Krkonoše museum in Vrchlabí by three weeks. The original deadline for opening the envelopes was 20 September, said national park spokesman Radek Drahný. The reason for the postponement of the deadline for submitting bids is the reduction of the budget from CZK 110 million to CZK 83 million.
"We are currently working with the prices that are on the market. There has been a change in the budget, it is the price that we expect to be offered. If someone submits an offer that is acceptable, then the work will start as soon as possible," said Drahný.
Compared to the original plans, the start of the repair of the museum is about a year late. KRNAP wanted to have a selected contractor for the construction part by the end of last year and start construction work this spring. According to the management of the national park administration, European subsidies of CZK 123 million for the project are not at risk.
The KRNAP administration has not managed to select a construction company for the museum repairs. It launched a second competition this summer because in the previous tender all offers from the companies significantly exceeded the then expected price of 65 million crowns. Bids exceeded 100 million crowns.
The museum, which is located in the former Augustinian monastery and belongs to the KRNAP administration, has been closed since autumn 2017. The selected company should provide the construction part of the project. The total cost, including the construction of a new exposition, is estimated at 210 million crowns. The KRNAP visitor centre should be created in the now cleared building by the end of 2021 after the transformation of the expositions.
The repaired museum with a new interactive exposition, which should be a story of nature and people settled in the mountains and follow up on the successful exposition Stone and Life, should serve as a representative entrance gate to the Giant Mountains for visitors. The visitor centre should provide the most comprehensible form of information about the past and present of the Giant Mountains and motivate people to discover the mountains and protect them. It should also take on the role of a traditional museum. The centre will also offer opportunities for concerts, festivals, theatre performances or open-air lectures. The plans include building a new entrance to the building, creation of a research room or a café.
