"Terrifying study result." Islam does not belong in the West, thinks overwhelming majority of Austrians
1,200 respondents were questioned, the survey shows considerable distrust of Islam in Austrian society.
Almost 60 percent of the population in Austria fears that some Muslims are terrorists, and 48 percent would demand the introduction of a ban on the construction of mosques. 80 percent are in favour of more monitoring of the centers of Islam.
A majority of Austrians also want Muslims to be restricted in their religious practices, claiming that the presence of Muslims sometimes makes them feel like foreigners in their own country.
"The study result is frightening," says study author Wolfgang Aschauer, adding: "Such a tendency towards ethnocentrism could eventually lead to the adoption of discriminatory attitudes. There is a risk that religious freedoms granted to Muslims will become narrower."
For believers, the critical stance is less pronounced. Aschauer argues that in Austria it is not a conflict between religions, but between cultures. Dialogue and education could help to blunt polarization, according to the sociologist.
According to the study, voters of the extreme right, those without a university degree or older than 75 years old hold the most hostile attitudes toward Muslims. Instead, Green voters, those under 30 and college students are the most welcoming.
According to estimates by the Austrian Interior Ministry, there are approximately 700,000 Muslims living in Austria, which has a population of roughly 8.7 million. The vast majority have Turkish roots. There are more than 400 Muslim prayers and mosques in the country, and Islam has been officially recognized as a religion since 1912.
Which Cities Will Disappear Under the Sea?
The vote by the upper house of Canada's parliament confirmed a familiar rumor for days: Canada is revoking the honorary citizenship of the former human rights legend, Nobel Peace Prize winner Do Aung San Suu Kyi. The current leader of Myanmar (Burma), who spent years under house arrest for trying to bring freedom to her country, lost her honorary title for her part in the genocide against the minority Rohingya nation.
The decision to revoke Suu Kyi's honorary citizenship was approved by the lower legislature a week ago, and has now been unanimously supported by senators. "This is the right message for her, for Myanmar, and for the world," said independent Senator Ratna Omidvar, commenting on the decision of her colleagues. "We must make it clear that accomplices to genocide are not welcome here in Canada - all the more so as honorary citizens."
The Canadian parliament's verdict technically changes nothing for Suu Kyi, it is just an honorary title, but on a symbolic level it is a powerful message for her. The silence of a long-time human rights activist on the atrocities that the army of majority-Buddhist Myanmar has been perpetrating against the Muslim Rohingya minority for endless months is intolerable.
The fact that an officially organized genocide is taking place in Myanmar, and that Suu Kyi - the de facto prime minister of the country's government - has utterly failed in her duty to protect her citizens, was recently reported in a UN report. Specifically, it mentions the names of several army commanders who, according to the investigation team, should stand trial for crimes against humanity committed in actions that, the report says, "shock with both the horror of their actions and the sheer scale of their actions." According to the UN, Suu Kyi and her administration have been complicit primarily in covering up the soldiers' actions and releasing a fog of lies around them by protecting them - such as an "anti-terrorist operation."
After Suu Kyi's removal, five figures remain on Canada's list of honorary citizens: the Swedish diplomat Raoul Wallenberg, Nelson Mandela, Tändzin Gjamccho, the 14th Dalai Lama, Karim Aga Khan IV, the 49th Imam of Shiite Muslims, and Malala Yousafzai.
Developments around the former icon of the fight for freedom and democracy have also been reflected by the Canadian Museum of Human Rights, where Suu Kyi's profile has been updated with information about atrocities against the Rohingya and a parliamentary decision to take away her honorary title. "We have also dimmed the illumination of her picture on a human rights timeline board and are thinking of replacing her face with a portrait of a member of the Rohingya minority," Canadian media quotes museum spokesman Rorie McLeod as saying.
The only thing that will remain in Suu Kyi's current turmoil - at least for now - is the Nobel Peace Prize, awarded to her at the suggestion of Václav Havel in 1991 for her enormous contribution to the fight for democracy. "While Suu Kyi's current actions are regrettable, her award will not be annulled," Nobel Foundation head Lars Heikensten told CBS Canada.
