Francis Fukuyama's history got a little screwed up. In 1992, at the height of the wave of liberalism that followed the end of the Cold War and the fall of the Iron Curtain, this political scientist wrote in his most famous book, The End of History and the Last Man, "What we may be witnessing... is the final point in the ideological evolution of mankind and the universal acceptance of Western liberal democracy as the final form of governance."
Twenty-six years later, we are rather witnessing, from the US to Russia, from Turkey to Poland, and from Hungary to Italy, rather illiberal models prevailing, and various forms of nationalism and radicalism thriving. Fukuyama's current ninth book, Identity: The Demand for Dignity and the Politics of Resentment, attempts to match the rise of these forces. As his interview with George Eaton for the New Statesman shows, many of his former positions are being reconsidered: he argues that the ideas of socialism should be put back into the public domain, and Marx was right about much of this. While he also insists that his intellectual development is still in line with the position of the 1990s, and critics of The End of History and the Last Man have misunderstood.
"What I said at the time was that one of the problems with modern democracy is that while it provides peace and prosperity, people want more than that... Liberal democracy doesn't even try to define what a good life is. It leaves it up to individuals who feel alienated, don't see the point, and therefore group together in identity groups that give them a sense of belonging."
At the time, The End of History and the Last Man was written as a powerful argument against Marxists who saw communism as the final stage of history. When Fukuyama is asked about how he now perceives the rise of socialists in Britain and the US, he replies, "It all depends on what you mean by socialism. If we're talking about ownership of the means of production, then, except when clear public services are demanded, I don't think it will work. But if you are referring to redistribution programs that attempt to address the huge imbalance in income and wealth that we are seeing, then yes. I think not only could he come back, he should come back. The long period that President Reagan and Prime Minister Thatcher started, in which certain types of ideas about the benefits of an unregulated market came to the floor, has had a disastrous effect in many ways."
Finally, Fukuyama tries to calm the current situation as well, warning all liberals that even the emergence of new not-quite-democratic regimes will not mean the end of history.
Civilization in Lent Time
I recently recalled a beautiful "line" from one of the great stories of Shimka and Grossmann, set partly in a cemetery, which reads: "I warned her that she cries well, but on someone else's grave!" It occurred to me that many of the world's politicians engaged in the senseless fight against climate change are now behaving very similarly.
They are behaving as if people were in control on planet Earth. In fact, we are just a speck on its surface, which she can blow out like a candle flame in a gust of wind. Probably not many of them are watching the famous British and American nature documentaries about the destructive powers of our blue ball. After all, all it would take is for one of the larger active volcanoes to make a big "fart" and our advanced civilization will shit itself out.
And that this will happen in the immediate future is highly likely. Many large volcanoes, in the opinion of leading volcanologists, are "charged and armed" (for example, Katla in Iceland).
In a way, it would be ideal if the eruption, if it must happen someday, should happen as soon as possible. Even before trillions of dollars are wasted on measures to reduce carbon dioxide production, because any properly angry volcano, along with dust and poisonous volcanic gases, can release at least a hundred times more into the atmosphere than has been saved at the expense of the people of Europe.
So violently limiting CO2 production makes no sense. Moreover, it has been scientifically proven that, with its significantly higher proportion in the air, plants form more biological matter and are also more resistant to drought. Possible warming is considerably more favourable for mankind than, for example, a rapid return of the Ice Age.
Considering the hitherto insufficiently studied influence of solar cycles on the Earth's climate, we must reach only one sensible conclusion: let us strive to keep the Earth as clean as possible, and let us adapt at least cost to other changes with which we cannot measure ourselves!
