Plane crash near Žinkov in Plzeň: Two people did not survive the accident
There were two people on the plane, a man (†63) and a woman (†38). "The plane at 8:30 p.m. asked for permission to land at the Chaloupky airport near Klatovy," police spokesperson Dana Ladmanová said. That was also the last record, at which time it was supposed to be located near Vojovice near Žinkov, according to GPS coordinates.
But it never reached the Klatovy airport. A search was immediately launched for the lost aircraft, which sent a distress signal. "In addition to the police, a military helicopter was involved," police spokesperson Martina Korandová said. But the search operation did not have a happy ending.
In the forest near Petrovic near Měčín, which is about six kilometers from where the plane last reported, a helicopter crew noticed the wreckage before 9 a.m. "We found the plane and two bodies with no signs of life," Korandová confirmed.
The crashed machine remained partially wedged in the branches of trees, and pieces fell on the ground nearby. "We will determine the cause of the accident in cooperation with expert experts and staff of the Institute for Professional Investigation of the Causes of Air Accidents," Korandová added.
Most of them are mild, only three percent of those infected need to go to hospital
Either a milder form of coronavirus is spreading through the Czech Republic, or a summer dose of sunshine has significantly improved our immunity.
Infectious wards of hospitals are half-empty, although the numbers of those infected are rising.
"The situation today and in April is completely different and it is mainly due to the number of hospitalized people," confirms Health Minister Adam Vojtěch.
It is worth remembering that on April 11, when the first wave of the epidemic peaked in our country, everyone wore masks, the army took samples, the republic was closed and the Czechs used disinfectant for the year ahead.
Nevertheless, ten people were dying every day.
Now the daily increases in the number of infected are higher, but every day with covid-19, a maximum of two people die.
Karvinsko still has the highest number of infected per population, similar numbers already have Jihlava due to an outbreak at the local Alzheimer centre, where there are already 57 infected - 40 clients and 17 employees.
Another home for the elderly has been closed by the sanitation department in Černozice in the Hradec Králové region.
Tests in one of the nurses confirmed the disease.
"We are tracing, we have reduced movement, we have all the hygiene measures," says Martin Scháněl, the director of the nursing home.
According to him, none of the home's clients have symptoms of the disease yet.
Health officials will start the blanket testing tomorrow and then decide on further measures.
Hospitals are also responding to the increased number of infections.
The Oncological Institute in Brno today launched an automatic camera system at the entrance, which can tell if people are wearing a mask when entering.
The record is reported by South Bohemian health officials, who recorded twenty-five cases of coronavirus - most of them foreign employees of the powder company.
Overall, there were 131 infections on Saturday - half of Friday's number - but there are fewer tests at the weekend.
Only children. We don't have reproduction, but we don't have to scare
Some words have ominous connotations, even if they only communicate the state of things. They include the word only child. It refers to a child growing up without siblings, but it doesn't sound neutral. "You know, only child," they say, without needing to add. Interestingly, this trait has always been carried by the "only child," back in the days when words like demographic crisis were not widely used.
Today, even people outside the scientific community know that a fertility rate of 2.1 children per woman is required to ensure simple reproduction of the population. It is also widely known that no state in Europe today achieves this level. France or Sweden, at most, is close to it, but European states are not assured of simple reproduction rates. (Within the West, only Israel stands out, with a combined fertility rate of 3.1 children per woman.) This is a situation made for alarmism. That's why it's no surprise when the minister of labor and social affairs, Maláčová, also falls for it: "There are almost as many only children as there are two-child families," she said in an interview with the LN. But she neglected the devil hidden in the detail.
Yes, it's good to draw attention to the problem instead of downplaying or ideologizing it. Like in Germany, for example, where the campaign for more children easily gains the label of fascism (in the style of "Hitler also supported it"). It's good to recall that many couples directly plan only children. It's good if politicians show the will to remove the obstacles that lead to those decisions (for example, the weak expansion of work from home discourages women from further pregnancies). But let's point out one thing.
When Minister Maláčová says that "there are almost as many only children" there is a hint of demagoguery. That statement was appropriate twenty years ago. Let's remember that fertility in the Czech Republic last ensured simple reproduction in 1980 ("Husák's children"). Then it dropped to a formidable 1.14 in 2000. But since then it has risen by almost fifty percent, to the current 1.70 children per woman, which is Europe's above average. It's not enough for simple reproduction, so the activity of politicians is appropriate. Only with this alarmism can they slow down a bit.
Neckermann cancels all flights, five hundred Czech clients involved
Neckermann cancels flights in connection with the insolvency of the British Thomas Cook and his German daughter.
"The Czech company Thomas Cook, s. r. o., operating under the business name Neckermann Cestovní kancelář, has not filed for insolvency," Šrámek said in a press release.
"CK Neckermann is, however, forced to continue cancelling the scheduled departures of its clients," he added, adding that this currently applies to all departures from 26 September to 6 October.
