The pair wrapped tape around the dog and drowned it in the river, the bag was found by the children
The case took place at the end of July in the village around Valašské Klobouk. A 27-year-old woman brought home a donated dog, one to two years old, which she wanted to take care of. But her ten-year-old partner didn't like the fact that it was a dog, so he decided to get rid of it.
"He wrapped the animal with duct tape and rope and significantly eliminated its vocal expression. He put the dog in a jute bag, which he tied up. Then they took the animal together to the river, where they threw it in the bag. At the moment when the dog was thrown into the water, the dog was demonstrably alive," said Zlín police spokesperson Monika Kozumplíková.
The following day, children playing by the river found a jute bag on the bank. When they opened it, they discovered the body of a dead dog inside. So they called out to a woman who was passing by and fled. The woman reported the incident to the police emergency number 158.
"Thanks to the knowledge of the townspeople they found out who is probably the perpetrator of this incredible act. And they were not wrong. Both the man and the woman confessed to the crime and described how the event took place," added a police spokesperson.
An expert statement from the field of veterinary medicine confirmed that the dog died unequivocally agonizingly as a result of suffocation, when the animal suffered within a matter of minutes before its death.
"The actions of the perpetrators undoubtedly show a clear intention to dispose of the animal at all costs in this reprehensible way, even though they could have donated or sold the dog. The criminal police commissioner from Zlín accused the couple of committing the crime of animal cruelty committed in complicity. The two so far unpunished accused could spend up to three years behind bars if convicted," Kozumplíková said.
The Declaration of the End of the Right in the House, or What "Right-wing" Coalition of ODS, TOP 09, STAN and KDU?
The media and commentaries have been reporting on the upcoming coalition of these parties recently. Many applaud that the "right" is finally coming together, but I am asking why these parties still call themselves right-wing.
Leaving aside the new Trikolora movement, the Czech Chamber of Deputies no longer has a real right-wing party. And it does not matter how these entities label themselves or what label is parroted by the mainstream media. ODS is hardly centrist in its average of top politicians of this party, TOP 09 is clearly a party of the urban pseudo-liberal left (which is ashamed of its leftism and thus hypocritically describes itself as conservative or even right-wing). STAN is a party which, in its conception, ideology and voter targeting, essentially merges with TOP 09 (the reason for its existence is simply not clear to me). And the KDU even labels itself as centrist in the long term - but their political compass is much more to the left than they say.
Do you feel that I have taken everyone out of the same water? No, I am based on the real political steps of these parties. If I consider myself to be a classically liberal right-wing voter, the highest value for me is individual freedom, free market and minimal state interference in the lives of individuals and the economy. How do these parties fulfil this general assumption of rightness? How many laws slashing people's freedoms by the salami method, increasing taxes, confirming new regulations and increasing surveillance, increasing the link to the socialist EU or supporting environmental and gender madness have they supported in recent years? A lot, a lot indeed. Not their own labels, but actions identify them. These parties, despite all sorts of declarations or partial concessions, want to strengthen the role of the state in our lives. And this has nothing to do with rightwing.
I wouldn't be surprised at TOP 09, STAN and KDU coalition cooperation, they simply belong together on the political map, and apart from the Christian or homosexualist and gender aspects, I basically don't see an obvious difference for the voters in terms of the state's influence on their lives. However, ODS has long portrayed itself as "the only right-wing" and by associating with these three entities it is already openly revealing its true political affiliation.
By the way, when I mentioned the labels briefly. Have you noticed how often all these parties quite consistently and cheaply refer to critics of dirigisme and socialism coming from the European Union as pro-Russian agents? Can't they or just don't want to understand that there are many people who don't like eurosocialism and increasing disenfranchisement as strongly as the authoritarian regime in Russia? Aren't they hiding their total argumentative incompetence and the unreasonable or blind adoration of the Euro-EU situation?
It's simply possible that in the Czech Republic other than centrist politics no longer has a chance of greater success. Maybe this is the kind of association voters really want. Maybe they want left-of-centre politics under the guise of the "right" because they are ashamed of their political beliefs (or can't even identify them). I don't know. But I certainly don't belong among such voters.
