Babiš calls for security cooperation at terror victims' memorial
Czech Prime Minister Andrej Babiš and his wife Monika visited Ground Zero in New York on September 27, 2019.
Terrorism is the main enemy against which all nations of the world should fight together. At the end of a five-day visit to the United States, Czech Prime Minister Andrej Babiš said today at the New York City memorial to the terrorist attacks of September 11, 2001. On this occasion, the Prime Minister honored the memory of the two victims of Czech origin.
"It's a very moving place," the Prime Minister said as he, accompanied by his wife Monika, laid a white rose next to the names of Lukáš Rambousek and the Czechoslovak émigré Alena Sešínová. Both were among the more than 2,750 dead claimed by the hijacked aircraft attack on the former pair of World Trade Center (WTC) skyscrapers. The towers of the WTC collapsed on impact, and in their place there is now a memorial with a list of the victims' names.
"We need to remember what happened here, the horror," said Babiš. The attack on the US on September 11, 2001 was cited by the Prime Minister as the reason why the UN should cooperate in a united campaign against international terrorism. The terrorists then, in addition to destroying the WTC skyscrapers, crashed the hijacked plane into the building of the Ministry of Defense in Washington and planned another strike on a target in Washington, probably the White House or Congress. But this aircraft crashed when the passengers confronted the hijackers.
"This is our main enemy, where all the countries of the world should come together and fight international terrorism in a coordinated way," the Czech Prime Minister added.
