Thank you for dancing! Singer Leonard Cohen's final album will be released posthumously
The album, Thanks for the Dance, will feature unreleased material and various musical collaborations put together by the singer's son. The album will be released on November 22.
In October 2016, the album You Want it Darker was released, on which Cohen collaborated with his son Adam. He asked Cohen to help him finish the songs. In the intimate recording, Cohen symbolically comes to terms with his impending death. He died a month after the album was released, at the age of 82.
Seven months later, Adam Cohen began working on the material left by his father. He invited a number of musicians to collaborate - Damien Rice, Bryce Dessner, Javier Mas, and the singer Beck, to name a few.
"When we invented the music for my father's words, we used his own distinctive musical techniques. So he's still with us," Adam Cohen told the album. "What amazes me most about him is the reaction of those who have heard him before. One by one, they say Leonard is still alive," he added.
The album's first swallow is the short song The Goal. "I'm almost alive, I'm almost home," Cohen sings in his distinctive honey voice. He sang about death, suspecting that he would not live to see the new material released. He admitted as much in an interview with The New Yorker a month before his death. "I'm ready to die. I hope it won't be too unpleasant," he said.
In September 2018, Adam Cohen published a collection of his father's poetry called The Flame. It will be published in Czech under the title Flame on December 31 by Argo.
