Travellers in almost every corner of the world can appreciate the convenience of paying with a card. This is especially true in popular tourist destinations, but today, payment cards are accepted almost everywhere. "People who travel more often, for example for work, do not have time to go repeatedly to currency exchange offices to exchange cash. And even "vacationers" do not want to rely on cash being enough for them. Moreover, some foreign currencies are not even available to Czech banks or currency exchange offices. We have therefore solved this with the NEO account so that its users can withdraw cash free of charge from all ATMs, wherever they are," says Kateřina Petko, Director of Marketing and Communications and Spokesperson for Expobank CZ.
Moreover, a payment card is a much more reliable way of not losing your money than cash. If a full wallet is lost, its owner may not wait for the money he carried in it. However, if he only loses his payment card, he can easily block it immediately over the phone or via internet banking. With quick action, he may not suffer any financial loss at all. "Keeping money in a bank account has other advantages besides its reliable protection. For example, the NEO account has an interest rate of 1.6% per year, which is among the highest among current and savings accounts. It is set up and administered completely online without the need to visit a branch. In addition, money in a bank account is insured up to EUR 100,000 and the account management is completely free," adds Kateřina Petko.
For anyone who is going to go abroad, travel insurance should be a matter of course. Thanks to the possibility of arranging it and paying by card online, it can be done even at the last minute. However, just owning a payment card often means insurance protection when travelling. "For example, with embossed MasterCard Gold and MasterCard Business cards, travel insurance is an integral part of foreign travel to all countries of the world. Holders of these cards can also insure their family with whom they are travelling. This often eliminates any other arrangements," adds Kateřina Petko from Expobank CZ. However, it is always advisable to check the scope of the insurance, i.e. whether it covers all activities that travellers plan to undertake.
The Ministry plans a flat-rate meal plan from 2021. Nothing changes in tax
The Ministry of Finance is preparing an amendment to the Income Tax Act, according to which an employee would receive money for meals directly. According to the Ministry, a quarter of employees, i.e. about a million people who do not yet receive meal vouchers, will also be able to support meals.
However, according to the chairman of the Voucher System Operators Association, David Rýc, even a number of small companies that do not have a canteen or meal vouchers provide meals for their employees, for example by importing food or by agreeing with restaurants.
"The essence of the plan is that we do not change anything about the tax advantage. Furthermore, it will not pay for health and social insurance," Schiller said on Friday. She added that the limit for the maximum employer contribution applicable as a tax credit would also be maintained.
The Income Tax Act allows companies to pay a maximum of 55 percent of the meal voucher price. The remaining part is paid by employees, in some cases by the employer, but without the tax credit. The most advantageous value of the meal ticket for employees and employers this year is CZK 123.
Bloomberg: Venezuela has hidden bitcoins and doesn't know what to do with them
Venezuela's central bank is conducting internal tests to determine whether it can hold cryptocurrencies. It is responding to an order from the state-owned Petróleos de Venezuela (PDVSA), which seeks to send bitcoins and ethers to the central bank and then pay the oil firm's suppliers with cryptocurrencies. Employees are also studying a proposal to allow the central bank to count cryptocurrencies in foreign exchange reserves, which are now near their 30-year low. Citing information from four sources, Bloomberg reported.
Sanctions imposed by the United States against President Nicolás Maduro's authoritarian regime have largely cut off Venezuela from the global financial system. This has exacerbated the country's economic crisis. The current crisis is one of the most serious in global terms, forcing officials to use a patchwork of different ways to move money. While Maduro's efforts to launch a state-owned cryptocurrency as the world's first failed, ongoing efforts to use digital currencies show how desperately the government is trying to find ways to circumvent the restrictions.
Neither the Central Bank of Venezuela nor PDVSA responded to a request for comment.
It is unclear how PDVSA came to own bitcoins and ethers, nor how much value it owns. The company is having trouble getting payments from customers through conventional channels, because large banks are unwilling to do business with entities that are subject to sanctions. Last month, the company received most of a $700 million (CZK 16.6 billion) payment in Chinese yuan, because the parties were unable to find financial institutions that would make the transaction possible.
PDVSA may have no appetite to sell cryptocurrencies on the open market, because that would require it to register on the exchange and undergo due diligence, a so-called due diligence. Instead, it wants the central bank to use the cryptocurrency and pay it to entities that PDVSA owes. Oil company officials believe the central bank is less exposed to any obstacles that might arise when paying with cryptocurrencies.
Bitcoins and ethers use a decentralized online ledger known as the blockchain to authenticate and record transactions. In some cases, relatively anonymous transfers are allowed without the need for an intermediary. Few banks are involved in digital currencies because of money laundering problems and client information that are related to them and complicate compliance.
Cryptocurrencies, after the 2018 debacle, are seeing a return to prominence this year, thanks to expectations of greater acceptance by institutions and Facebook's plan to come up with its own cryptocurrency. Even so, they remain unstable. Bitcoin has fallen nearly 20 percent in the last four days, but has made a profit of about 130 percent since the beginning of the year.
Jan Šindelář's commentary: Running the railways like a company
Sky's election, although perhaps not entirely smooth, is the conclusion of a sad story about the state's inability to give the railways a clear direction. The board of directors has been incomplete for over a year now, and even after Wednesday evening, that remains the case, as one of the members has resigned. The interim is ongoing.
The selection process itself has been a farce from the beginning, if only because the requirements for candidates, especially in the field of practice, have been significantly relaxed. Compared to the selection last year, the requirements for the size of the company in which the candidate should have worked in the past have been reduced. First, the members of the selection committee, and then the supervisory board, played only the role of pimprlat.
Sky submitted perhaps the weakest professional CV of the five finalists, yet without the practice of a large company, it beat the experienced guys from the management of logistics giants as well as transport companies. Participation of interesting managers from the private sector was perhaps the brightest side (and the greatest hope) of the whole process. Today, those concerned know that they played only the role of narrative scenery in the political game.
Maybe they will surprise Nebeský, show great talent, and in the end he will prove to be the best railway boss of all time. At least in the beginning, however, it will be accompanied by the aftertaste of political travesty. Czech Railways is not facing an easy period, it has to cope with competition in market liberalization and lack of employees in operation. There are no train drivers, shunters and mechanics. What motivation should they have for further work and respect for management if the state behaves like an elephant in a china shop in the top management?
The second important group is creditors. How they interpret the games at the head of the railways will be seen next spring, when the railways defend the rating. What is certain is that creditors perceive instability. Sadly, someone else comes to Moody's agency every year to defend the rating for Czech Railways. The agency has not missed the frequent changes in the management of the railways and the political influence on the company, it criticized them already this summer.
The ANO movement coins, among other things, the slogan that the state must be managed as a company. For a start, it would be enough if it managed one big state company as a company and not as a state. ČD is still one of the largest companies in the country and it would be good if the best ones led it. They applied, but the state scorned them. It can certainly be argued that the post at the head of the railways has always been a political matter. But then we can avoid the antics of the tender procedure.
An unusually open and unique image of Karel Gott in Olga Špátová's feature-length documentary
This unique film feature by Olga Špátová will be premiered in Czech cinemas next spring.
"In mid-September last year, Ivanka and Karel Gott called me and asked me if I would make a documentary about his life with Karel again after ten years. I didn't hesitate a minute! Shooting with a man who lasted more than half a century on the limelight of Czech culture thanks to his exceptional singing talent, artistic humility and immeasurable diligence, was and is a great honour for me. I accepted the invitation to make a feature-length documentary film about Karel Gott, who brings joy to three generations of listeners with his art, as a commitment to this legendary singer," director Olga Špátová describes her feelings.
Thanks to a quick agreement and agreement, the first shooting day took place already on 22 October last year and the last shots with Karel Gott were shot a few days ago. The goal was and is absolutely clear - to capture authentically Karel Gott as a phenomenal singer who gives himself away to his supporters, as a painter, but at the same time as a loving husband and father of his children. A man who for sixty years with his songs gives joy to several generations not only in our country, but also in Europe, and indeed all over the world. A man who has written himself into the hearts and souls of his listeners by simply being.
The film is not meant to be a parade of Karel Gott's undisputed fame and his achievements. "Therefore, it is not even possible to compare my previous film The Gott Phenomenon with this current one. Everyone is different. At least because we filmed them at a different stage of Karel Gott's life, and this will be very evident in his personal, almost intimate confession, which he gave us and which confirmed us all in what a legend we have the opportunity to work with and spend time with, which is truly indescribable," adds Olga Špátová.
The creators captured Karel Gott during his performances, during meetings with his fans in our country and in Hamburg, but especially in his home environment, whether in Prague, in a cottage in Czech Switzerland, in the village where he spent his childhood, and in other places that played an important role in his life. The film will thus be completely authentic and unique thanks to Karel Gott's sincere openness.
"Olga has a great gift for filming with her narrow team in such a way that we often let ourselves get carried away by the spontaneous atmosphere and naturally let her into our privacy, thanks to which I talked about topics quite intimate. She and her husband, the cameraman Jan Malíř, actually became part of our family. Originally, we wanted to release the film in 2019, when I celebrated my life's jubilee. But because I had a beautiful summer with my family, I wanted us to shoot as long as possible. Well, and because there was a lot of me in 2019, my wish was that it would be released in cinemas next spring. This documentary film is a thanks to my supporters and all those who supported and guided me in my profession," Karel Gott himself says about the film.
