Police charge CzechTourism manager Aleš Pangrác over promotion contracts
Police have charged a former manager of the state agency CzechTourism, Aleš Pangrác, over promotion contracts. Pangrác confirmed to the news server Seznamy Zprávy that he took over the charges this week. Czech Television (ČT) reported last year that officers in the case were examining contracts worth CZK 38 million. Some of the money, according to the police, was going back to Pangrác, the news server reports. In the case, the criminal investigators were also interested in the Minister for Regional Development, Klára Dostálová (for ANO), whose department CzechTourism belongs to. The investigation into the case continues, according to the news server.
Detectives from the National Centre against Organized Crime secured evidence in this case in the second half of last November. They were, for example, at the headquarters of the Ministry for Regional Development, at the headquarters of CzechTourism, at the autodrome in Most or at the agency Sport Invest. The service computer was also taken from the minister's apartment. The court search warrant for Dostálová, previously cited by ČT, said that the minister decided in 2016, when she was a deputy, on CzechTourism's expenses for the benefit of the chosen persons through mediation and outside the standard of official procedure. Dostálová said at the time that she felt absolutely innocent, she did not doubt, she could document everything and she cooperated fully with the police.
According to the agency, it was the fault of an individual. The media reported earlier that it was the former director of the regional partnership department at CzechTourism, Aleš Pangrác, who was dismissed due to the results of the audit. This showed that the CzechTourism agency had concluded 48 problematic contracts.
"Yes, they accused me. But I don't want to comment further," Pangrác told the server Seznam Zprávy.
