Stores destroyed, street fires, memorial procession followed by riots
Five years ago, 43 students of a university in Ayotzinapa disappeared, despite extensive investigations, the case has not yet been solved. The students were allegedly detained by police in the Mexican state of Guerrero. It is not clear exactly what happened after that, but according to the investigation, the students apparently ended up in the hands of a local syndicate and were subsequently killed and burned, reports APTN.
On Thursday, a memorial procession was held in Mexico's capital, families wishing to express their frustration that answers and explanations for their children's disappearance were still not being found.
But the largely peaceful march was disrupted by smaller groups of vandals, who destroyed everything in their path. Vandals destroyed shops and hotels, did not shy away from destroying monuments, set fires around the city and blew out windows.
Even before the march, President Andres Manuel López Obrador said he would do everything to catch them, and asked the public for any information that would lead to a clarification of the case.
Over 142 people were detained as part of the investigation, but none of them were convicted. Many of them had to be released because their human rights had been violated, investigators allegedly had to torture the suspects, adds APTN.
Putin on the phone with Zelensky ahead of Donbass ceasefire, Kremlin criticizes planned elections
Russian President Vladimir Putin spoke on the phone with his Ukrainian counterpart Volodymyr Zelensky about the situation in Donbass, where a new ceasefire is to take effect from midnight.
Putin, according to the Kremlin statement, criticized, among other things, the decision of the Ukrainian parliament to hold local elections; Kiev reported that Zelensky called for the release of the detained Ukrainians.
A new ceasefire was agreed on Wednesday evening by the negotiators of Ukraine and Russia, supported by the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE).
The ceasefire is to begin after midnight on Monday night, is to be "complete and universal" and is to open the way for fulfilling other provisions of the peace agreements.
In the interview, Putin told Zelensky that the decision of the Ukrainian parliament to hold local elections contradicts the Minsk peace agreement and threatens the prospects for a settlement of the conflict in eastern Ukraine.
The Ukrainian parliament decided last week that the forthcoming local council elections will not take place in territories controlled by pro-Russian rebels.
The Minsk agreement foresees that Kiev will regain control of the border of Ukrainian territories occupied by separatists with Russia after giving these regions wide autonomy and holding local elections there.
According to Unian, Zelensky's office said that the two statesmen agreed on the benefits of the upcoming ceasefire in Donbass as well as on the need to implement other measures to support peace in the region, such as de-mining areas of fighting or withdrawing part of the troops from the front.
Zelensky also called on Putin to release Ukrainians detained in eastern Ukraine, the occupied Crimea peninsula and Russia itself.
The Minsk agreement has helped to stop the fighting, but people continue to die in occasional firefights and artillery attacks on both sides of the front.
The conflict in Donbass has resulted in over 14,000 deaths since spring 2014.
Ukraine and the West accuse Russia of military support for the separatists, which Moscow denies.
Zelensky has made ending the war in Donbass his priority, but no major breakthrough in negotiations has yet taken place.
And where are the spectators? Doha Can't Be London
But it is also a step backward, for in its pilgrimage to Doha, athletics has voluntarily and consciously renounced the thrilling atmosphere of a sold-out stadium in London 2017, as well as the European Championships in Berlin last year.
Giant banners on the walls of skyscrapers in Doha invite "the biggest sporting event of 2019." Nevertheless, concerns grow about how dignified its backdrop will be.
"Tickets for the finish line are sold out for all evenings," the organizers say.
But that is too little.
The upper gallery of the Khalifa Stadium, with a total capacity of 40,000 spectators, is already covered with brightly colored tarpaulins, which also display the flags of the 209 participating countries. Athletics has set out in Qatar for a territory where it has no roots, despite the annual Diamond League meeting.
No wonder, then, that only 50,000 tickets were sold for the 10 days of the Championships last week, although their price started at 60 Qatari riyals, or less than 400 crowns.
The organizers have now set themselves the goal of filling the uncovered portions of the stands at least half full. That is why, according to sources in the British newspaper Giuardian, they are reportedly (though the organizers themselves deny it) giving away free tickets to migrants who work here as workers, as well as to children. Which Sebastian Coe, the head of the IAAF athletics association, can also say positively: "That is how we can inspire the next generations."
Rich Qatar has won world championships in handball and cycling in the past, after athletics comes football in 2022. The financial offerings of an oil-rich power will always be lucrative, even for rich sports federations. That is the reality of today's sports world.
But even if we accept it and ignore the absence of fans in the stadium, we cannot help but feel a genuinely sporting sigh that the IAAF leaders should have timed the experiment with the first outdoor World Athletes' Championships in the Arabian Peninsula better - and for another year. The extreme late deadline, imposed by the climate, disrupts the entire scheduling of the pre-Olympic season, and thus the preparation for the pivotal Olympic season, which would normally begin for athletes in October.
Perhaps Qatar will make up for this with at least the technological innovations with which it promises an ultra-modern and attractive championship. Isn't it just 37 degrees? Already, the stadium's surface is artificially air-conditioned to 24 degrees. And advanced cameras, embedded directly in the blocks, are designed to show even television viewers in detail what happens to athletes in the hundredths of a second before and just after the starter's shot.
