Annex 7 / Classification of incidents
The items below are only inspirational. This annex must be accurately and exhaustively formulated by the project manager.
Incidents from the operational environment
A category A incident means Incident in the operational environment if, for example:
the user cannot log into the Application
if the Application repeatedly falls at the same step and the user cannot complete the critical process
if the system shows too long (double the defined performance parameters)
responses to user activity
if it is not possible to print the documentation or report for the client
if incorrect data are shown to the end customer
Critical functionalities/processes Applications are:
account creation or cancellation
daily shutdown startup
A category B incident means an Incident in the operating environment if for example:
the user's work is slowed down but does not seriously affect the workflow
if non-critical functionality is not available to the end customer.
A category C incident means an Incident in the operating environment if for example:
if it is a language defect or a font other than the agreed font
if it is a graphic error in the user interface that does not confuse the user in the use of the interface
if it is a Documentation defect
Incidents from the acceptance environment
A category TA incident means an Incident in the acceptance environment if for example:
it is not possible to start a client in the system
A TB category incident means an Incident in the acceptance environment if for example:
it is not possible to change any of the parameters of the client account
A TC category incident means an Incident in the acceptance environment if for example:
when it is a language defect or a font other than the agreed font
when it is a graphic error in the user interface that does not confuse the user in using the interface
when it is a Documentation defect
