Overview of bank accounts for children in the Czech market
Children's accounts are provided free of charge by banks. However, it is necessary to consider the offer, as some other services to the accounts are already charged. "The motivation of banks to offer accounts for children, whose basic management is usually free, is straightforward. Financial houses count on their waived fees being refunded one day. With the small migration of Czechs between banks, they are probably not wrong," says Kristýna Kuncová from dTestu.
"Small accounts," she says, can do almost anything that adult accounts can do. A child gets his own payment card, can enter payments, track account movements, and has his own electronic banking at his or her disposal somewhere. Banks set up the account, but it is up to parents to teach children how to use them and also check their payments.
"Relatively flexibly, a parent can set weekly or monthly limits, turn individual services on and off, and so on. Above all, however, he or she can monitor what is happening on the account, whether by looking over the internet or thanks to information SMS. Beware, these may no longer be free," Kuncová adds, adding: "If a parent is considering an account for their child, they should consider the child's abilities and options."
Museum in Semily returns to the Velvet Revolution with exhibition
An imitation of a normalisation room with a television in which footage of the brutal intervention of police officers against students on 17 November 1989 in Prague is shown. This is also in the museum's new exhibition in Semily, which is dedicated to the Velvet Revolution. "The basis is to present what happened in Semily after the events on Národní třída," said the exhibition's curator, Tomáš Chvátal.
"I would say that the atmosphere was basically the same everywhere, with the first demonstration in Semily on 22 November, and then gradually more people were packed up every day," he said. Among the most active was a group of local dissidents around Miroslav Matěcha, who was the only one from the town and the immediate surroundings to sign Charter 77, and Mr and Mrs Dědečková, who were expanding the Several Sentences petition. The Civic Forum was also created relatively quickly, according to Chvátal. "One specificity is that there was a very strong group of local doctors in the Civic Forum," said the curator.
Some 50 photographs should draw visitors into what was happening in the town at that time, the pictures were taken 30 years ago by Karel Bárta. A video of the general strike on 27 November 1989 by František Tomíček has been preserved, which will be looped throughout the exhibition. Ivan Hlas also spoke and sang at the demonstration. The Semily Archives also lent a number of preserved banners to the exhibition at that time. "They said: Let's not get drunk with a bun, From trough to trough, We don't want violence," said Chvátal. Some of the changes in the town were very rapid at that time, for example, as early as December, people decided in an all-Semily vote that the square would be Riegrovo and abolished the previous name of Gottwaldo.
The exhibition also captures what was happening before the November events. "In the first part, we present to both the witnesses and students what was before, such a late normalization. I think we have managed to collect unique documents from Semily, whether they are banners with various communist slogans or a bronze plaque from the then-museum of the workers' movement," Chvátal said. One room is supposed to create a feeling of what it might have been like in the living room of an ordinary household at that time.
The last part of the exhibition is again devoted to what happened after the Velvet Revolution. It focuses on the first free elections. "We wallpapered one room with election posters. Those who have experienced this will remember over the posters With us to Europe or there is Václav Klaus still under the OF banner with the beautiful motto Everyone for his community," added the curator.
A pike in a pond or a relatively affluent open-air museum?
Babiš chose for his optimistic view statistics such as good security (the Czech Republic is seventh in the world), low unemployment rate, low national debt. Or the fact that our country is, according to one recent study, the 24th in quality of life out of 140 evaluated countries.
Developer Dušan Kunovský and architect Josef Pleskot, in a television interview on the occasion of the Architecture and Development Summit, however, cited other, far from "rosy" data. For example, the Czech Republic is 154th in the world in speed of construction proceedings. It may be that the current economic "boom" will not leave behind any significant building heritage as it was in the past.
The biggest obstacle is not only the existing legislation, but also the slow, inefficient bureaucracy. Comparative studies show that the Czech Republic lags significantly behind the developed countries in the overall quality and performance of public administration.
Our country has simply not yet managed to make good use of the potential of the good economic situation of recent years to invest in the future. It is nice that salaries and pensions are increasing, but people with improved living standards will also want to have a place to live, travel modern and fast, have quality cultural stands, live without an intolerable environmental burden.
But in the capital Prague, for example, it has not been possible for years to complete the inner and outer circuit or to build a speedway or a metro to the airport. And Prague does not even have a modern, architecturally daring national library, concert hall, or national gallery. The reason for this is not only absurd wrangling over architectural competitions, zoning plans and building permits, but also some specifically Czech conservatism, which adheres to the motto "any bolder change is for the worse."
And when it seems that something bolder could succeed, it will almost certainly be thwarted by monuments or other somewhat stubborn societies, or politicians. In the absurd drama surrounding Jan Kaplický's "blob" designed for the new building of the National Library, even President Václav Klaus wanted to tie himself to the backhoes.
The list does not end with Prague. The Czech Republic is not able to complete its backbone motorway network or start building train speedways, so Germany has finally decided to lead its tracks for superfast trains from Berlin to Vienna by a "detour" through Bavaria. Moreover, repairs to existing infrastructure are often drowned in shenanigans. Getting quickly from Prague to Brno is now a puzzle.
Babiš came into politics promising to "get things done." But not much has happened so far as meaningful investments and acceleration of cumbersome bureaucratic procedures are concerned. An amendment to the law on the acceleration of construction of transport infrastructure is in force from 2018, but we will have to wait for the larger beneficial impacts of, for example, easier land expropriation. And a new building law, approved by the government, which should reduce the current average length of construction proceedings from 5.4 years to one year, will, if we are lucky, start to apply from 2021. But many people would probably not bet on it.
