Protests in Bulgaria: Pig ears thrown by demonstrators at government building
Participants in a demonstration against Bulgarian Prime Minister Boyko Borisov and his cabinet threw pig ears at the government building.
It was another in a series of protests against the "mafia style of governance" that have been taking place in Sofia and other cities for almost three weeks.
Organizers are planning a nationwide blockade on Wednesday, DPA reported.
Today's protest, which took place for the 18th consecutive day, had a weaker turnout than the previous one, according to Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty.
At 8 p.m. some 300 people had gathered, some streets had to be closed to traffic.
Demonstrators outside the government building staged a theatrical stunt in which they symbolically locked both Prime Minister Borisov and Attorney General Ivan Geshev in a prison cell in connection with the arrest of two aides to President Rumen Radev, who is a strong political opponent of the Prime Minister.
The resignation of both is one of the protesters' basic demands.
They also demanded the cancellation of the announced health care reform and an end to corruption in construction on the Black Sea coast.
Protest organizer Nikolai Hadjigenov said on public radio today that a "peak of escalation" is planned for Wednesday in the form of a "nationwide rally in Sofia and blockades throughout the country."
He reiterated the demand for the resignation of Borisov and his government, as well as the calling of early elections.
The regular elections should take place in March 2021.
Borisov has previously said that he does not intend to resign.
He justified this by, among other things, the need to carry Bulgaria through the covid-19 pandemic and the resulting economic crisis.
But on Friday he replaced five members of his government team, although the concession did not reassure the demonstrators.
Earlier this week, Borisov's government withstood a vote of confidence in parliament.
Attorney General resumes prosecution of mother who manipulated daughter against father
Attorney General Pavel Zeman disagrees with the acquittal of a mother who manipulated her daughter for a long time and interfered with her relationship with her father. She faced charges of abuse and endangering her upbringing. The regional court acquitted her, Zeman disagrees. Such behavior can be seen as a criminal act, according to his appeal to the Supreme Court.
The Supreme Court ruling could have a broader impact on other cases. "A more specific definition of such a specific form of abuse can be considered necessary also from the point of view of directing further application practice," reads Zeman's appeal.
Last year, the District Court in Svitavy first found the woman guilty of abuse of the person entrusted to her and endangering the upbringing of the child. She formed a strong, even symbiotic bond with her daughter, even in a situation where she was supposed to be entrusted to her father.
The result was a pathological fixation on the mother and a significantly negative relationship with the father. The situation marked the emotional development of the daughter, who was even hospitalized. She threatened to self-harm in case of transfer to the father's custody.
The Svitavy court sentenced the mother to two years in prison with a two-year probation period. However, the Pardubice branch of the Regional Court acquitted the woman on appeal, saying it was not a criminal offense. The Regional Court repeated the same verdict even after the Supreme Court once ordered it to rule again.
The Regional Court found that situations in which one parent manipulates a child against another are not exceptional. They are resolved in guardianship proceedings, possibly with the help of psychologists or social protection authorities for youth. Only exceptionally is the solution criminal law.
According to the Prosecutor General, however, the woman committed both abuse and endangering the upbringing. "The accused acted in a completely deliberate manner, stirring up negative feelings towards her father in her daughter, and she purposefully reinforced these negative emotions. By acting in this way, she not only pursued the illicit intention to limit or exclude the father's contact with a minor, but she must have been aware that this would cause negative consequences in the psychosocial sphere of the minor," the appeal reads.
Zeman asked the Supreme Court to refer the case back to the Regional Court once again. The appeal states that the child is now in the father's custody. ____________________________________________________
