The launch of the new toll is not at risk, reports Kremlík. But a change of operator is in play
On Friday, the Ministry of Transport launched preparations for a new tender for the operation of the new toll system. It is a back-up plan that the state would use if the current toll contract were to be definitively cancelled. In addition, the state is also preparing another provisional solution if the tender is not completed in time. On Facebook, the Minister of Transport Vladimír Kremlík (for YES) said.
On Thursday, the Office for the Protection of Competition (ÚOHS) banned the performance of the toll contract between the state and the CzechToll/SkyToll consortium, with a one-year delay. The ministry will file an appeal against this.
"The launch of the new toll collection system is not at risk. Starting today, we are starting the preparation of a new transparent tender, the subject of which will be the services of the operation of the new toll system, which is now being completed by the CzechToll and SkyToll consortium," said the minister.
The state would thus be looking for the operator of the currently prepared toll, which will be launched from this December. It would therefore not be a competition for a completely new toll system, as was the case with the last tender, nor for the use of the old system, which is now operated by Kapsch.
However, according to Kremlík, the ministry is also preparing for the fact that it would not be able to prepare the new tender in time. "Based on the experience so far with the toll tender process, I am deeply convinced that the ÚOHS is wrong and that it is objectively impossible to prepare and implement such a complex tender procedure and to hand over the operation of the toll system to the new operator within the 12-month period specified by the tender," he said.
The ministry will thus be preparing a provisional solution in addition to the new tender procedure, which would solve the toll collection for a transitional period until the state finds a fully-fledged form of solution.
The state will thus probably not use the offer presented to it by the current Kapsch toll administrator in recent days. The Austrian company offered the state to operate the existing system in case the toll contract was cancelled.
At the same time, Kremlík reiterated that he believes that the backup plan will not be needed. The ministry will therefore file an appeal against the antitrust authority's decision.
The ÚOHS issued a decision on Thursday in which it prohibited the toll contract from being fulfilled. However, the ban will only take effect one year after the authority's decision becomes final. This is not final and it is possible to file an appeal against it to the president of the authority. The ministry and CzechToll therefore continue to prepare the new toll, which should be launched in December.
The CzechToll/SkyToll consortium won last year's tender for the new toll system and its operator. It succeeded in the toll tender with an offer of 10.75 billion crowns for the 10-year operation. The current Kapsch operator protested against the tender and the validity of the toll contract, which failed in the tender with an offer of over 13 billion crowns.
