Insects are up to 60 times fewer than 40 years ago
No other animal class is more represented in nature than insects. Beetles, butterflies and other species make up more than half of life on Earth. But there are increasing reports that the insect kingdom is shrinking radically. Another scientific study on the subject came out just this week, and the situation is even more serious than humanity has previously realized.
The study is based on field research in the tropical forest of Puerto Rico, in which American scientists copied a similar survey from 1976. As they write at the beginning of the report, insects in the forest today are "10 to 60 times fewer." It is the decline of the entire population, not the number of species, and the research involved not only insects but all arthropods. Because of the insect extinction, the population of other fauna that depend on insects in the food chain, such as birds, frogs or lizards, is also shrinking.
The authors of the research put their conclusions in direct connection with climate change. The average air temperature in the forest has risen by two degrees Celsius in the last thirty years, they say, and warming has become the driving force behind the collapse of the food chain. According to the authors' team, the study shows that the impact of climate change on tropical ecosystems may be much greater than previously thought.
The report was published on Monday in a big article in the Washington Post, which reports the new findings as hyperalarming. "It's one of the most disturbing articles I've ever read," David Wagner, an entomologist at the University of Connecticut, told the paper, citing him as an independent expert.
Insect extinctions also affect Europe. "In our country, the decline is also of the order," points out Lukáš Čížek of the Academy of Sciences' Entomological Institute. But in addition to climate change, it is also necessary to take into account landscape changes that play an essential role in Europe. "In our country it just runs for a significantly longer time than in Puerto Rico," adds Čížek, explaining why scientists could measure such a rapid decline in the forest compared to the 1970s.
