Hundreds of enslaved children freed from religious school in Nigeria
According to the BBC, there were nearly five hundred men and boys there, Reuters reported, citing the police commissioner, that there were over three hundred children from the age of five upwards. Some were chained together, others were chained to iron rings in the wall.
Kaduna Police Chief Ali Janga told the BBC that the raid on the school was based on a tip-off. He described the school as a house of horrors. Starving people were held there by force, tortured and sexually abused. They could not leave, there was razor wire above the walls. He said it was a case of slavery.
Several people were detained during the raid, according to police spokesman Jakubu Sabo, who was a teacher there.
The children told police that they were taken to the school by parents or relatives, saying it was a religious school. "We have identified two children who come from Burkina Faso, but most of them were brought here by parents from Nigerian states in the north," said Sabo's spokesman on the identity of the victims. Nigerian states in the north of the country are predominantly Muslim.
Imam Ahmad bin Hanbal's school was posing as a religious school focused on the study of the Koran.
Those freed were taken to a stadium where they are provided with help and food. Some have already met relatives.
The fastest man on the planet has missed his tests. I don't take anything, he fights back
The traditionally high-profile race for the fastest man on the planet will be the hunt for defending silver champion Christian Coleman at the World Championships. The 23-year-old American is the world leader with a time of 9.81 seconds and has lost only once this year. But his start at the peak of the season was in jeopardy due to a case of missed doping tests.
The United States Anti-Doping Agency (USADA) closed his case in early September without filing charges for formal reasons. Although Coleman failed three doping tests last year and this year, not in 12 months. His first offense was backdated by the World Anti-Doping Agency (WADA) to April 1, 2018, the start of the second quarter, but he missed the test itself on June 6. And because the third omission occurred on April 29, 2019, Coleman did not commit a offense in the form of three missed checks in 12 months.
Coleman argued that he only forgot to update the data on the athletes' whereabouts app. "I don't take drugs or anything legal. A lot of athletes use legal creatine or protein powder or other supplements for faster regeneration. And I don't take anything, I work hard and that's what it's all about," he said before the start of the World Championships.
His only defeat in six of this year's 100 was when he entered the season at the Shanghai Diamond League, where he was just six thousandths of a second ahead of compatriot Noah Lyles. He took advantage of Coleman's absence to triumph in the Diamond League final, but will only run the 200 at the World Championships.
On paper, the second fastest competitor is 22-year-old Nigerian Divine Oduduru, with a 9.86, but he has only done so far at American college competitions.
The defending champion will be 37-year-old American Justin Gatlin, who flashed a 9.87 at Stanford in June. He ran the last 100 in Zagreb in only 10.29, however, as he slightly injured his posterior thigh muscle.
South Africa's Akani Simbine, the three-time Olympic medalist from Rio Andre de Grasse and the European champion Zharnel Hughes are also among the favorites. The fastest Jamaican is the 2011 World Champion Yohan Blake with a 9.96 time.
