Soldiers rehearse, draw the curtains. China prepares celebrations at massacre site
The army rehearsed the parade over recent weekends. Shops in central Beijing had to close, and residents near the square were ordered to close the curtains. Military vehicles rolled toward the square on empty streets, and combat aircraft circled in the sky.
Several Chinese told Reuters they were proud that their country would display its military might. But one woman said it was hard to deny that the celebrations would unsettle other nations.
She seemed to be referring to Taiwan, which China claims, and where elections are coming. But they may also be worried in the semi-autonomous city of Hong Kong, where thousands of people have repeatedly demonstrated against China's appointed administrator.
Celebrations are being prepared outside Beijing. The southern Chinese port of Xiamen already put on a special light show on Thursday night. Xiamen lies across from island Taiwan and is one of China's top ten most innovative cities.
Before the anniversary, the list of banned items is growing. It already includes drones, balloons, dragons, alcohol, radios and radio-wave devices, the Guardian pointed out. It added that China's popular social network Weibo erases "damaging political information."
"This is another milestone, another opportunity to show that China's Communist Party remains (at the oar) despite all predictions," said historian Maura Cunningham, who works on China. "This is the moment when the Party can demonstrate order, control and power," she added.
The People's Republic of China was established in 1949 when the Communists under Mao Zedong won a battle with Chiang Kai-shek's Nationalists, who retreated to Taiwan.
In the second half of the 1960s, China underwent a disastrous Communist experiment in the form of the so-called Cultural Revolution. In June 1989, the Tiananmen Square regime massacred thousands of pro-democratic protesters, both students and workers, with tanks.
Since the late 1970s, China has increasingly taken over elements of the capitalist economy. According to critics, it is now a mixture of the worst of communism (one-party monopoly and persecution of the opposition) and (Dickensian) capitalism (exploitation of workers).
