Germany reports the first case of West Nile infection from a mosquito on its territory. Linked to climate change
In addition to West Nile, mosquitoes can also transmit malaria.
On Friday, Germany reported the first case of a human being infected with West Nile fever on German territory after being stung by an infected mosquito. The DPA news agency reported. Until now, all sick people have contracted the virus while travelling or through contact with sick animals. Experts say the breakthrough case is linked to climate change.
The Robert Koch Institute said the virus was contracted by a 70-year-old man from Saxony. The disease was severe and he was treated for brain inflammation in a hospital in Leipzig. He is now healthy.
The West Nile virus was first detected in 1937 in Uganda. Meanwhile, it spread to large parts of Africa, Asia and Europe, and in the 1990s to the United States. Its carriers are mainly birds, as well as mosquitoes that become infected with their infected blood.
