Trump considers deregistering Chinese stocks in the US
US President Donald Trump's administration is considering revoking Chinese firms' permission to trade on stock markets in the United States. An informed source told Reuters today. Such a move would be a radical escalation of trade tensions between the US and China. Shares of the firms in question on the New York Stock Exchange immediately headed down following the news, dragging the entire market down with them.
The withdrawal of the shares would be part of a broader effort to curb US investments in China, the source added. He confirmed a Bloomberg report that had sent financial markets into shock shortly before. Shares of Chinese firms Alibaba Group Holding, JD.com, Pinduoduo, Baidu, Vipshop Holdings, Baozun and IQIYI were down from two to four percent.
According to government data from February, 156 Chinese firms are trading on the US Nasdaq and NYSE stock exchanges. There are also at least 11 state-owned enterprises among them.
Bloomberg pointed out that no precise mechanism has yet been devised to ensure the withdrawal of Chinese companies from the US exchanges. Any plan would have to be approved by Trump, who has given the go-ahead for negotiations on the matter.
China and the US have been engaged in a trade war for more than a year, imposing tariffs on each other. The dispute between the two countries has had negative effects on the world economy and has raised fears of a global recession. Washington is using tariffs to try to get Beijing to change its trade practices and reduce China's trade surplus with the US.
According to CNBC, trade negotiations between the US and China should resume on October 10. It aims to end the trade war.
Former French President Chirac to be buried on Monday, public commemoration on Sunday
The funeral of former French President Jacques Chirac, who died on Thursday at the age of 86, will take place on Monday evening at the Montparnasse cemetery in Paris. French media are reporting the news, citing Chirac's family. The ceremony will be private.
The public will be able to bid farewell to the former head of state on Sunday afternoon at a commemoration ceremony at the Paris Invalides, where the coffin containing Chirac's remains will be on display, the Élysée Palace announced.
Crowds have been pouring into the presidential residence since Thursday evening, according to AFP, to sign a book of condolences. This will be possible until Sunday. On Monday, President Emmanuel Macron declared a state of mourning.
Meanwhile, there have been further reactions from around the world and from France to the death of the former mayor of Paris and president from 1995 to 2007, whom Prime Minister Édouard Philippe today called "a Frenchman in the truest sense of the word."
Chirac was remembered by the Japanese, for example, because the politician was known for his love of their country and the sport of sumo. The news of the death of the former French president appeared on the front pages of all Japanese newspapers, including the sports ones, the French press notes.
The museum of tribal art on Paris's Quai Branly avenue, which Chirac founded, will not charge admission for ten days in honour of the former head of state.
Arctic Spitsbergen set a temperature record, measuring almost 22 degrees
"Longyearbyen set a 41-year-old record," the Norwegian Meteorological Institute said on Twitter.
By early evening, the temperature had risen to 21.7 degrees Celsius, 0.4 degrees above the 1979 record, it added.
The roughly 2,000-strong Longyearbyen is the largest city on Spitsbergen, located about 1,300 kilometres from the North Pole.
Spitsbergen heats up faster than almost any other place on Earth.
This highlights the dangers of warming in other parts of the Arctic - from Alaska to Siberia, according to a report last year by the Norwegian Center for Climate Study.
The average temperature on Spitsbergen has risen by three to five degrees since the 1970s, he said.
It may even rise by ten degrees by 2100, if greenhouse gas emissions to the atmosphere are not reduced.
Temperature rises on Svalbard can melt permanently frozen soil, threatening the stability of many buildings, roads or airports, and may cause more avalanches and landslides.
Warming climate also threatens Arctic fauna, such as polar bears or seals, which depend on the ocean's ice cover.
