The government committee should completely reject candidates who do not meet the conditions. These will include criminal integrity, debt-free status, a minimum age of 25 years and the main selection criterion should also be expertise.
The law will still have to pass the Senate and will then be signed by the president.
The car tuner has brought the voice of the digital soul
Everything you know about obesity is wrong, says the headline of a long text written for the Huffington Post by Michael Hobbes and photographed by Finlay Mackay. In a provocative twist, it says that for decades the medical community ignored the facts about obesity and waged a fierce (and also unnecessary) war against overweight people that not only tainted public opinion but also destroyed many lives. But now is the time for a new paradigm.
What Hobbes says right from the start is that there is often a very long and tedious journey from knowing and knowing facts to putting them into practice. He mentions the case of scurvy, with some captains as far back as the seventeenth century handing out lemons, limes, and oranges to their crew in the belief that they would prevent the disease. But the British Navy abandoned the practice because of fears of increased costs. The clear influence of fruit in preventing and treating the disease was then demonstrated in the mid-18th century, but it took another fifty years for the Navy to take this into account. Seat belts also existed long before the invention of the car, but they only became mandatory in the sixties, and the first confirmed asbestos-related death dates back to 1906, yet its first ban came in 1973.
"Every public health discovery - no matter how significant - has always had to compete with traditions, prejudices, and financial incentives within the society into which it was to be implemented," Hobbes writes. In American society today, nearly 80 percent of the adult population, and about one-third of children, meet the definition of overweight or obesity. More Americans now live with obesity than with breast cancer, Alzheimer's, Parkinson's, and HIV combined.
Obesity is seen as an eminently personal failure of the individual, which is claimed to burden health care and reduce GDP. The fear of fat is so great in the population that Americans now spend more money on diets than they spend on computer games and movies. But the truth is that diets don't work. Back in 1959, research showed that 95% to 98% of attempts to lose weight ended in failure, and two-thirds of people on diets subsequently gained more than they lost.
Armed with statistics, Hobbes goes on to describe the lifestyles and traumas of overweight people. The personal meets the systemic, with, for example, only 19 hours of study time devoted to nutrition in faculty teaching future doctors. Which, at a time when 60% of the calorie process Americans take comes from ultra-processed food - that is, too much processed food.
How obesity is stigmatized is illustrated by reports from surgeries, where overweight people tend to experience shorter checkups, with doctors approaching them with less empathy and viewing them as more problematic patients.
But, far from being an American problem, Hobbes writes, since 1980, obesity rates have doubled in 73 countries around the world, and increased in 113. And in that time, no country has been able to reduce and stop this increase. Absolutely none.
