Duplantis has a mile-long lead, it's a kick in the ass, laments Swede's challenger
The 22-year-old American pole vaulter has the ambition and potential to be one of the new ruler's most serious competitors.
He already knows what it's like to beat the two-year-old Duplantis, defeating him last year at the NCAA Universities Association meeting.
"We had a battle the year before, he won and I was second, then we switched places.
It was a very good fight both times," describes Nilsen, who secured the victory with 5.95 meters.
But Duplantis has since shot up sharply and currently finds himself alone in the highest pole-vaulting spheres.
At just 20 years old, he became the world record holder, breaking the 6.17 meter bar in Torun on February 8 this year, adding an inch a week later in Glasgow.
"He was jumping six meters at the age of 18 when he graduated from high school," recalls his peer Nilsen for the World Athletics website.
"It was clear that once he matured from boy to man, he would increase his potential and talent tenfold.
Twenty years is a pretty good age to jump a world record," he believes.
While Nilsen's list of accomplishments is noticeably thinner than that of Duplantis, the American has similar goals.
He has hinted at his options so far at NCAA races, which he has won regularly, improving his indoor personal best to 5.93 metres at one in February this year. He won a gold medal at the Pan American Games in Lima last August, having already fought his way into America's quest for the World Championships in 2017, where he finished 13th.
The next milestone for him is to get his first taste of the Diamond League.
"It's definitely my priority to get on the professional circuit and compete as much as possible in the Diamond League, because you can make a name for yourself there," he realizes.
"If you can succeed at this level, you can undoubtedly do the same at events like the Olympic Games, the World Championships or the Pan American Games."
But the pandemic has delayed these peak holidays, giving Nilsen and the other pole vaulters time to improve.
But will that be enough to catch up with Duplantis, who can easily turn a race under five rings into a mere silver match?
"Everyone's trying to catch up, but I don't think that's going to be possible anytime soon," Nilsen muses.
"The kid's been jumping for 16 years, and he's a mile ahead of everyone else in practice."
And he'll want to increase it even more before Tokyo 2021 begins.
Scientists are looking for toddlers with a birth defect called ankle valgozita for their study
The ankle valgozita is a birth defect that affects five to ten percent of children. It is normally treated with intensive exercise. Scientists are trying to help these children even more, so they have developed a special shoe that should significantly speed up the treatment.
"We have two prototype shoes that will be worn by healthy children and children with a diagnosis to map the effect in both groups. Participation in the research will have no risks for the children and the measurement will be completely painless," explains Marta Gimunová, head of research at the Faculty of Sports Studies at MU.
Parents of both groups of children can apply for the study via the web, where a registration form and all information is available.
Scientists are looking for fifty children with a diagnosis and fifty healthy children. Of each group, half will always wear health shoes and half will not.
"The moment when parents should enroll their child is when they start taking the first separate steps, typically letting go of the furniture they hold when trying to walk. Participation in the research involves three measurements within seven months of the child's first steps, each lasting about 20 minutes, and for half of the participants it also includes wearing the tested shoes," Gimun points out.
The opening of Pumpkin World delayed the ripening of pumpkins
Nová Ves u Leštiny (Havlíčkobrodsko) - A farmhouse in Nová Ves u Leštiny in Havlíčkobrodsko opened Pumpkin World for more than a month today. Decorations consisting of thousands of freshly harvested pumpkins are dominated by massive orange pyramids in the garden. The autumn event, which is becoming a tradition, starts one week later this year because the pumpkins ripened longer in the surrounding seven hectares of fields belonging to the Pipkova family. Even now there are many of them in the field, Jaroslava Pipková told ČTK today.
The Pipkos grow many types of pumpkins, but the weather has not favoured them for the last two years. This year's harvest was delayed and some types did not work out. "As usual, we have enough orange pumpkins for Halloween, but some types for fine people have failed," said Pipková. Nevertheless, there are more types to choose from on the farm, from the already mentioned large pumpkins suitable for carving and digging decorations, through pumpkins for cooking hokaido or elongated "spaghetti" to ornamental pumpkins of various colours and shapes.
Pumpkins are laborious to grow. Farmers manually hoe the plants and harvest the fruit, cutting the pumpkin from the stem with scissors. Pumpkin World The Pipkos have been opening regularly since 2010, and previous years have attracted thousands of people. Pumpkin decorations are complemented by attractions made of straw or a maze of logs. Visitors will also see animals raised on the farm. It will be open daily until November 3.
Details of the event are available on the farm's website, where growers also offer some recipes for pumpkin dishes, including pumpkin muffins or juice. Visitors themselves tell them about other options for pumpkin preparation in the kitchen. "A lot of cooks have tried their recipes, and we will be inspired as well," Pipková said. She noted that some housekeepers also put pumpkins on sour like cucumbers.
