Uncombed wants 45 million from the state
According to the spokesperson of the office Vladimír Řepka, the Ministry of Justice has received six applications in this connection so far and is now analysing them. The young man was in jail for two years for assaulting a woman, but the judiciary eventually acquitted him.
The appeal in the case was not lodged by the Attorney General Pavel Zeman or by the Minister of Justice Marie Benešová.
The attempted murder of the hairdresser in Hořice happened in February 2013. The Hradec Public Prosecutor's Office indicted the then 20-year-old high school student, Nečesaný. The prosecution alleged that he hit the woman several times in the head with a log and then took over ten thousand crowns from her. The seriously injured woman was found by her son and her life was saved by the doctors of the Hradec hospital.
Nečesaný denied any wrongdoing from the beginning. "I am innocent and I swear to it. I am sincerely sorry about what happened to the victim, but I am not the perpetrator," the young man, who did not deny that he was at the hairdresser's on the fateful day, said earlier in court. He said he wanted to get a haircut. But he left after his wife told him that he was already closing. He then turned himself in as a witness to the police.
The hairdresser did not recognize him as the aggressor during questioning at first, but later identified Nečesaný as the attacker. According to forensic experts, she suffered from memory lapses after the attack.
The Hradec Regional Court handed down five sentences in succession in the case. At first, Nečesaný was convicted twice and sentenced to 16 years in prison, while the High Court of Appeal reduced his sentence to 13 years. Nečesaný gradually headed for prison twice, but each time he was freed after the Supreme Court intervened. After the ordered replacement of the Judicial Chamber, acquittals were eventually handed down repeatedly, the last one being upheld by the High Court in March this year.
However, the Chairman of the Appeal Chamber, Jiří Lněnička, also stated in the grounds of his conclusions that this decision was wrong, but due to the procedural situation, he said he did not have a better option. He said that he rejected the prosecutor's appeal against the acquittal verdict, even though her appeals were justified.
"The problem with this case is not that there is a lack of evidence, but its evaluation. We believe that sufficient evidence was gathered in the preliminary proceedings, which in another criminal case would have been more than sufficient for an admission of guilt," said Lněnička.
However, both the Hradec and the Supreme Court viewed the case differently and said their opinion would probably not be changed by further annulment of the acquittal.
