The tenant is entitled to interest on the security from its provision at the statutory rate.
V. Rights and obligations of the contracting parties
The landlord undertakes to:
- leave the subject of the lease to the tenant so that he can use it for the agreed purpose, maintain the apartment and the house in a condition suitable for use for the duration of the lease, and maintain the house in a proper order customary according to local conditions for the duration of the lease
- remove the damage or defect within a reasonable time after the tenant has notified him of the damage or defect.
If the landlord does not remove the damage or defect without undue delay and properly, he may remove the damage or defect to the tenant and request compensation for justified costs, or a discount on the rent, unless the damage or defect is not substantial.
If the tenant does not notify the landlord of the damage or defect without undue delay after he has had and could have ascertained it with due care, he is not entitled to reimbursement of costs; if he removes the damage or defect himself, he is not entitled to a discount on the rent.
- to ensure the tenant's undisturbed use of the subject of the lease during the term of the lease
- to carry out other maintenance of the subject of the lease and its necessary repairs, which the tenant is not obliged to carry out
Rights of the tenant:
- if this does not cause an increased burden on the apartment or house, the tenant may also work or do business in the apartment
- to keep an animal in the apartment, unless the breeding causes the landlord or the other occupants of the house difficulties disproportionate to the conditions in the house.
If the breeding causes the need for increased costs for the maintenance of the common parts of the house, the tenant is obliged to reimburse the landlord for these costs.
- to carry out, with the landlord's consent, modification, alteration or other alteration of the apartment or house.
If the landlord does not consent to a change which is necessary due to the disability of the tenant, a member of his household or another person living in the apartment, without having a serious and fair reason for refusing consent, the landlord's consent shall be replaced by a court, at the tenant's request.
At the end of the lease, the tenant is obliged to remove the alteration he has made in the apartment or house, unless the landlord requests the restoration of the previous condition.
- to accept anyone in his household.
If the tenant accepts a new member of his household, he is obliged to notify the landlord without undue delay of the increase in the number of persons living in the apartment; if the tenant fails to do so within two months of the change, he is deemed to have seriously breached his obligation.
The landlord has the right to require that only a number of persons live in the tenant's household that is proportionate to the size of the apartment and does not prevent everyone from living in the apartment in normal comfortable and hygienically satisfactory conditions.
If the number of members of the tenant's household decreases, the tenant is obliged to notify the landlord without undue delay.
Obligations of the tenant:
- to use the apartment properly in accordance with the lease agreement
- to observe during the period of the lease the usual rules of conduct in the house and reasonable instructions of the landlord to maintain the proper order usual according to local circumstances
- to carry out and pay for the normal maintenance and minor repairs related to the use of the apartment
- to tolerate modification of the apartment or the house, or its reconstruction or other change, only if it does not reduce the value of the housing and it can be carried out without major inconvenience for the tenant, or if the landlord carries it out on the orders of the public authority, or if there is a direct threat of particularly serious injury.
In other cases, the change can be carried out only with the consent of the tenant.
- if the tenant finds damage or defect in the apartment that must be removed without delay, he shall immediately notify the landlord; he shall notify the landlord without undue delay of any other defect or damage that prevents normal housing.
The tenant is obliged to do what can be expected, according to his ability, to prevent further damage from arising from damage or defect which must be removed without delay.
The tenant is entitled to reimbursement of costs expediently incurred in preventing further damage from occurring, unless the damage or defect was caused by circumstances for which the tenant is responsible.
- if the tenant knows in advance of his absence from the apartment, which is to be for more than two months, and of the fact that the apartment will be difficult to reach him during this period, he shall notify the landlord in good time.
At the same time, he shall notify the person who, during his absence, will ensure the possibility of entering the apartment in case it is strictly necessary; if the tenant does not have such person at hand, the landlord shall be such person.
If the tenant fails to fulfil his obligation, this shall be considered a breach of the tenant's obligations in a serious manner; this shall not apply unless there is serious damage for this reason.
