VI. Sublease
The tenant may sublease part of the apartment to a third party only if he himself resides in the apartment.
Section 2272 of the Civil Code applies mutatis mutandis.
If the tenant does not permanently reside in the apartment himself, he may sublease the apartment or part of it to a third party only with the landlord's written consent.
The application for consent must also be made in writing.
If the landlord does not respond to the application within one month, the consent is deemed to be given.
If the tenant breaches the aforementioned obligations, he is deemed to have grossly breached his obligation.
The sublease ends together with the lease.
If the lease ends, the tenant is obliged to inform the sublease in a timely manner, indicating the relevant facts, which are in particular the date of expiry of the lease, the length of the notice period and the beginning of its running.
If the tenant, in accordance with the law and this contract, allows a third party to use the item, he is liable to the landlord for the conduct of that person as if he were using the item himself.
VII. Termination of the lease
When the item is handed over, the tenant is entitled to separate and take everything he has put into the item or brought into it at his own expense, if possible and if this does not impair the substance of the item or make it excessively difficult to use it.
If the apartment ceases to exist during the period of the lease, the lease shall end.
If the apartment ceases to exist in part during the period of the lease, the tenant is entitled either to an appropriate discount on the rent or to terminate the lease without notice.
Termination of the lease requires a written form and must be given to the other party.
The notice period runs from the first day of the calendar month following receipt of the notice by the other party.
In the event of termination by the landlord, the latter is obliged to inform the tenant of his right to object to the termination and to propose a review of the validity of the termination by the court.
The landlord may terminate the lease by giving three months' notice only for the reasons stated in Section 2288 of the Civil Code, he is obliged to state the reason for the termination in the notice.
The lessee has the right to apply to the court to examine whether the termination is justified within two months from the date on which the termination was received.
The landlord has the right to terminate the lease without notice in accordance with Section 2291 of the Civil Code.
