a. if he has not paid rent and service costs for a period of at least three months,
b. if it damages the apartment or house in a serious or irreparable manner,
c. if it causes otherwise serious damage or inconvenience to the landlord or persons living in the house; or
d. if the unauthorised use of the dwelling is otherwise or for a purpose other than that agreed.
If the landlord does not state in the notice what he sees as a particularly serious breach of the tenant's obligation, or if he does not call upon the tenant, before the notice is served, to remedy his defective behaviour within a reasonable time or to remedy the unlawful condition, the notice shall be disregarded.
The tenant is obliged to hand the apartment over to the landlord on the day when the lease ends.
The apartment is handed over if the landlord receives the keys and otherwise nothing prevents him from accessing and using the apartment.
If the tenant leaves the apartment in such a manner that the lease can be considered to have ended without any doubt, the apartment is to be deemed to have been handed over immediately.
The tenant is obliged to hand over the apartment in the condition in which he took it over, notwithstanding the normal wear and tear during normal use and the defects which the landlord is obliged to remedy.
The tenant is obliged to remedy changes in the apartment which he has made with the landlord's consent, if the parties have agreed to restore the apartment to its original condition at the end of the lease.
The tenant is obliged to remedy the changes he has made to the apartment without the landlord's consent, unless the landlord informs the tenant that he does not request the removal of the changes; nevertheless, the tenant cannot claim compensation even if the changes increase the value of the apartment.
The landlord may claim compensation in the amount of the reduction in the value of the apartment caused by the changes made by the tenant without the landlord's consent.
Fixtures and objects fixed to the walls, floor and ceiling of the apartment which cannot be removed without a disproportionate reduction in value or without damage to the apartment or house are transferred by affixing or insertion into the owner's ownership of the apartment.
The tenant has the right to demand that the landlord settle with him without undue delay; this does not apply to what the tenant has done without the landlord's consent.
The compensation is payable at the latest on the date of termination of the tenancy.
The landlord is entitled to compensation in the amount of the agreed rent if the tenant does not surrender the apartment to the landlord on the day of termination of the tenancy, until the day on which the tenant actually surrenders the apartment to the landlord.
If an item remains in the apartment that can be considered to belong to the tenant or to a member of his household, the landlord takes care of the item for the benefit of the tenant and on his behalf.
If the tenant does not take over the item without undue delay, the landlord has the right to sell the item in an appropriate manner after having given the tenant adequate additional reasonable time to take over the item, after giving notice to the tenant on his behalf.
This does not apply if the item is clearly abandoned by the tenant or a member of his household.
The tenant may terminate the lease if the circumstances on which the parties appear to have relied in incurring an obligation under the lease have changed to such an extent that the tenant cannot reasonably be required to continue the lease.
In the event of the tenant's death, the contract is governed by Section 2279 et seq. of the Civil Code.
