He will receive another honour in memoriam, the current president Miloš Zeman (75) is supposed to award him the Order of the White Lion and honor his memory.
Heat threat in the Czech Republic as of Tuesday, meteorologists warn of fires
Weather warnings of high temperatures are valid for Tuesday afternoon for the whole of Bohemia, with the exception of the Karlovy Vary Region, as well as for southern and central Moravia.
"Exceptionally, temperatures may exceed 34 degrees Celsius, especially in central Bohemia," they state.
They recommend people to follow a drinking regime in the heat and limit their body load in the noon and afternoon hours.
Due to the warm weather with a minimum of rainfall, there will be a risk of fires starting on Tuesday morning.
Windy weather could contribute to their rapid spread.
Weather warnings about the risk of fires apply to central Bohemia, including Prague, Liberec, Ústí nad Labem, Karlovy Vary and the Pilsen Region.
Fire warnings will be in force until further notice.
"We do not expect significant rainfall that would alleviate the danger in the northwest and west of Bohemia until at least the end of the week," says ČHMÚ.
The Prague Municipality responded to the weather warnings by banning the setting of fires in risky places, which should apply from Tuesday.
People in the capital will not be allowed to set open fires in parks, gardens or forests, for example, up to 50 meters from the edge of the forest growth.
Smoking and the use of pyrotechnics are also prohibited in these places.
The measures will apply until further notice, Prague Municipality spokesperson Vít Hofman informed.
French chef sues Michelin over star removal I'm depressed, he says
The renowned French chef Marc Veyrat lost his third Michelin star this January, a year after winning it. He plans to sue the publisher of the Red Guide to obtain the exact reasons for the demotion. Veyrat also questions the competence of Michelin inspectors, who, he says, mistook saffron for cheddar. The first trial is scheduled to take place in November.
The chef of the famous La Maison de Bois restaurant in the Alpine region of Upper Savoy lost one of his three Michelin stars in January this year. He will sue the publisher of the prestigious Le Guide Michelin because, he says, the commissioners' conclusion was not properly substantiated. Moreover, the removal of the star, he says, took place without any notice. "I've been depressed for six months. How dare you mess with the health of the chefs?" Veyrat told the commissioners.
Michelin only gave the chef vague reasons, such as that the chef put cheddar in the souffle, which the inspection did not like. "I put saffron in it and the gentlemen thought it was cheddar because it was yellow. I have been lovingly working with Savoy ingredients from the beginning," he said, protesting against the decision of Veyrat. He is convinced of the strong incompetence of the Michelin commissioners: "You are frauds who only cause controversy for commercial reasons." Outraged, Veyrat cannot understand "how they could dare say that we put cheddar in our souffle." "They insulted our region as well, my employees were mad about it. We have eggs from our hens, milk from our own cows, gardeners gather fresh herbs every morning," he said.
The distinctive chef, always wearing a black hat and dark glasses, is opposed to the new generation of Michelin commissioners and therefore asks for his restaurant to be excluded from the red guide. But the publisher refuses to do so. "If the business remains open and our inspectors re-select it, we will continue to recommend it," says Gwendal Poullennec, Michelin's international director.
According to Michelin, the chef's lawsuit shows that he has no meaningful accusation yet and a lawyer is yet to help him formulate it. "We regret that Mr. Veyrat communicates rudely with us. But we will examine his comments carefully," he said.
In addition to La Maison de Bois, Marc Veyart owns two other three-star restaurants.
